<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Mac App Store (MAS) entitlements for Mathilda Notebook.

  These entitlements are applied at SIGNING time by the MAS build
  (tauri.appstore.conf.json -> bundle.macOS.entitlements). They have no effect
  on plain .dmg builds.

  Placeholders ($IDENTIFIER, $TEAM_ID) MUST be replaced before signing — either
  by editing this file or, preferably, by passing a rendered copy. See
  docs/appstore.md.

  Entitlement rationale:

  * com.apple.security.app-sandbox (MANDATORY for MAS)
      Every App Store app must run inside the App Sandbox. This is the entire
      reason the sidecar had to be made self-contained: sandboxed apps cannot
      load dylibs from /opt/homebrew.

  * com.apple.application-identifier = $IDENTIFIER
      Must EXACTLY equal tauri.conf.json > identifier (currently
      "com.mathilda.notebook"). Apple matches this against the App ID and the
      provisioning profile. Format is usually "<TEAMID>.<bundle-id>" in some
      contexts, but for the application-identifier entitlement Apple expects the
      bundle identifier here; keep it identical to the app's bundle id.

  * com.apple.developer.team-identifier = $TEAM_ID
      Your 10-character Apple Developer Team ID. Must match the certificate and
      provisioning profile.

  * com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write
      REQUIRED. The notebook opens and saves .lb notebook/library files via the
      Tauri dialog plugin (open/save panels in frontend/src/App.svelte). Under
      the sandbox, an app may only touch files the user explicitly picks in an
      NSOpenPanel/NSSavePanel; this entitlement grants read-write access to
      those user-selected files. Without it, open/save would silently fail.

  NOTE (deliberately omitted):
    * com.apple.security.network.client / .server — NOT included. The engine
      runs as a local sidecar communicating over stdio pipes; there is no
      network use anywhere in the app or engine. Add network.client only if a
      real network feature is introduced.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
    <true/>

    <key>com.apple.application-identifier</key>
    <string>$IDENTIFIER</string>

    <key>com.apple.developer.team-identifier</key>
    <string>$TEAM_ID</string>

    <key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
